> Strategy - Compact keywords

Input : (Session Id, project_id, file_name, code block, identifier)

A given code block can be represented in a much more compact way than we formally write in a program.

For example
A function like:
// Before
void processCustomerOrderWithValidation(Order& order, Customer& customer) {
    validateOrderItems(order);
    applyCustomerDiscounts(customer, order);
    ...
}
//After
void f1(Order& C1, Customer& C2) { f2(C1); f3(C2,C1); ... }

Not just method names, this can be extended to class names and the imported packages/library names.
And the storage of the mapping is delegated to the sessionStore module.

EXCLUSION RULE:
Built-in / primitive types that are part of the language itself must NEVER be compressed.
They must appear in the output exactly as written in the source.
This rule is language-agnostic. Examples of names that must be left unchanged:
  C/C++   : void, bool, char, int, short, long, float, double, unsigned, signed,
             size_t, auto, wchar_t, int8_t … uint64_t
  Java    : void, boolean, byte, char, short, int, long, float, double
  Python  : int, str, float, bool, bytes, list, dict, tuple, set
  Go      : bool, byte, rune, int, int8…int64, uint…uint64, float32, float64,
             complex64, complex128, string, error, any, uintptr
  JS/TS   : string, number, boolean, void, never, any, unknown, object, symbol, bigint
  Rust    : bool, char, str, i8…i128, u8…u128, f32, f64, isize, usize

Output : (Session Id, compressed code block)